Answer: Here is a basic Maven `pom.xml` template for compiling a Java project:

```xml
<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
  xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 http://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd">
    <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

    <!-- Project Information -->
    <groupId>com.example</groupId>
    <artifactId>my-java-project</artifactId>
    <version>1.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
    <packaging>jar</packaging>

    <!-- Project Name and Description -->
    <name>My Java Project</name>
    <description>This is my Java project.</description>

    <!-- Project Properties -->
    <properties>
        <project.build.sourceEncoding>UTF-8</project.build.sourceEncoding>
        <maven.compiler.source>1.8</maven.compiler.source>
        <maven.compiler.target>1.8</maven.compiler.target>
    </properties>

    <!-- Project Dependencies -->
    <dependencies>
        <!-- Add your dependencies here -->
    </dependencies>

    <!-- Project Build Settings -->
    <build>
        <plugins>
            <plugin>
                <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
                <artifactId>maven-compiler-plugin</artifactId>
                <version>3.8.1</version>
                <configuration>
                    <source>${maven.compiler.source}</source>
                    <target>${maven.compiler.target}</target>
                </configuration>
            </plugin>
        </plugins>
    </build>

Answer: To create an LCD control system using a potentiometer and temperature sensor, you can follow these steps:

1. Connect the LM35 temperature sensor to the Arduino board via VCC & GND pins, and connect the analog output pin of the LM35 temperature sensor to the analog input pin A0 of Arduino [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].
2. Connect a 10 K Ohm potentiometer to control the brightness of the LCD panel. The second pin of the potentiometer should be connected to pin 3 of the LCD [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].
3. Install the LiquidCrystal_I2C library by Frank de Brabander in the Arduino IDE [[2](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-display-temperature-from-lm35-sensor-on-lcd)].
4. Upload the code to the Arduino board using the Arduino IDE [[2](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-display-temperature-from-lm35-sensor-on-lcd)].

Note: The provided search results do not provide a complete code for the LCD control system. However, you can find a code example for displaying temperature from an LM35 sensor on an LCD in [[2](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-display-temperature-from-lm35-sensor-on-lcd)]. You can modify this code to include the potentiometer control for the LCD brightness.

2. **Define**: The product designer defines the problem statement and the design goals. This involves identifying the key challenges and opportunities for the product.
3. **Ideate**: The product designer generates a wide range of ideas for the product. This involves brainstorming, sketching, and prototyping.
4. **Prototype**: The product designer creates a prototype of the product. This involves creating a tangible representation of the product that can be tested and refined.
5. **Test**: The product designer tests the prototype with real users. This involves gathering feedback and iterating on the design.
6. **Refine**: The product designer refines the design based on the feedback and testing results. This involves making adjustments to the design and iterating on the prototype.

To configure Apache Airflow to support Azure Active Directory (AAD) Single Sign-On (SSO) tokens, you will need to set up OAuth2 authentication in Airflow. This involves configuring Airflow to use Azure AD as an OAuth2 provider. Below is a step-by-step guide to help you generate the necessary configuration code for your `airflow.cfg` file.

### Prerequisites

1. **Azure Active Directory (AAD) Setup**: Ensure you have an Azure Active Directory set up and have registered an application for Airflow. This will provide you with a client ID and client secret.
2. **Airflow Version**: Ensure you are using an Airflow version that supports OAuth2 authentication (Airflow 2.x).

### Step 1: Gather Azure AD Application Details

- **Client ID**: The client ID of your Azure AD application.
- **Client Secret**: The client secret of your Azure AD application.
- **Tenant ID**: The ID of your Azure AD tenant.
- **Authorization URL**: `https://login.microsoftonline.com/{tenant_id}/oauth2/v2.0/authorize`
- **Token URL**: `https://login.microsoftonline.com/{tenant_id}/oauth2/v2.0/token`

### Step 2: Configure Airflow for OAuth2

You will need to configure the `[api]` and `[core]` sections of your `airflow.cfg` file to support OAuth2 authentication with Azure AD.

#### Example Configuration

```ini
[api]
auth_backend = airflow.api.auth.backend.default

[core]
authenticate = True
auth_type = OAuth2

[oauth]
